article.title: In Photos: Blue-Green Rivalry Ends in Tie
article.description: Harder Stadium filled with 11,424 people on Saturday for the Blue-Green Rivalry, breaking records as the largest crowd in the country this season for a men’s soccer game.
article.content:
Josue Salgado clears the ball after a clean slide tackle. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

Kevin Feucht stumbles over Cal Poly defenders. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

Nick DePuy and Jan Ilskens receive hugs while preparing for a corner kick. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

Members of the audience come up to the side of the field, cheering for the camera. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

Ahinga Selemani rushes to keep the ball from rolling out of bounds. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

Sean Dhillon crosses the ball. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

Ahinga Selemani races for control of the ball. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

Fans cheer and tortillas are thrown after a favorable call. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

After leaping over a defender, Jeff Quezada heads the ball upfield. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

The clean up crews had to work hard to keep the field clear of tortillas thrown throughout the game. McLane Brown / Daily Nexus

Jan Ilskens wrestles the ball away from Cal Poly’s Justin Dhillon during the last minutes of the match. Courtesy of Kenneth Song

Titouan Le Roux anticipates his next move as the game goes into overtime. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

UCSB’s Lamar Batista and Cal Poly goalie Eric Kam battle to control the ball during the final minutes of the double-overtime match. Courtesy of Kenneth Song

Nick DePuy out-maneuvers the SLO defense. Eric Swenson / Daily Nexus

At the end of two overtime periods, the match was still scoreless. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

UCSB librarian Margaret Rankin collects tortillas after the game. Dustin Harris / Daily Nexus

UCSB Guest Services crew pick up tortillas after the match. Courtesy of Kenneth Song

related.title: In Photos | Blue-Green Rivalry Renewed at the Thunderdome
related.description: UCSB was able to defend its home court for the fifth consecutive year against rival Cal Poly, defeating the Mustangs by a final score of 65-56.
related.content:
In front of its best crowd of the season with over 4,800 people in attendance, the UCSB men’s basketball team was able to hold off its bitter green rival, Cal Poly, and improve to 12-3 on the year and it also picked up its first Big West win of the season :

related.title: In Photos: Deltopia 2016
related.description: Daily Nexus photographers captured all of Deltopia weekend, from parties to power outages to The Warm Up concert featuring Grouplove.
related.content:
Photos by: Lorenzo Basilio, John Clow, and Vivian Bui

Horses were stationed just outside the IVFP office for most of the day, with occasional exercise. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
A skateboarder hitches a ride behind his friends. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Vivian Bui / Daily Nexus
UC Isla Vista, a volunteer group formed by the A.S. Public Safety Commision, hosted water stations and handed out “the perfect package” of condoms and cookies. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Vivian Bui / Daily Nexus
Approximately 3,500 people attended this year, dwindling down to about 500 by sunset, compared to a peak of 25,000 in 2014. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Volunteers handed out free food at the Jesus Burgers post on Del Playa Drive. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Vivian Bui / Daily Nexus
Despite the lack of attendance at this year’s Deltopia, students still enjoyed the first weekend of spring quarter. Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Lorenzo Basilio / Daily Nexus
Despite the power outage, people were still able to order pizza and drinks at Pizza My Heart (though they had to pay in cash). John Clow / Daily Nexus
Authorities struggle to control the fire and restore power to businesses during the Deltopia power outage. John Clow / Daily Nexus
